        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-02-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-02-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="73"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                <head>73. Memorandum From the Naval Aide of the Presidentʼs Military Representative
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BWH1" type="from">Bagley</persName>) to the
                    Presidentʼs Military Representative (<persName corresp="#p_TMD1" type="to"
                        >Taylor</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d73fn1">Source:
                        National Defense University, <persName corresp="#p_TMD1">Taylor</persName>
                        Papers, T-133-69. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1962-02-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 19, 1962</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>As a follow-up to the recent poor press in Saigon and the moratorium on U.S.
                    newsmen riding in U.S. aircraft,<note n="2" xml:id="d73fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d48">Document 48</ref>.</note> State approached the President
                    Saturday, 17 February, to pin down a future policy.</p>
                <p>The State proposal gives Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_NFEJ1"
                        >Nolting</persName> authority to decide on press participation in U.S. air
                    operations on a case-by-case basis. He will be governed by the policy to
                    emphasize the U.S. support function and the <gloss target="#t_SVN1">SVN</gloss>
                    primacy in winning the war. Military and other advice will be rendered through
                    the Country Team.</p>
                <p>The State position was developed with the positive interest of Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName> and Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName>, but was not concurred in by Governor
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d73fn3"
                        >See <ref target="#d59fn1">footnote 1, Document 59</ref>.</note> It was
                    presented to the President by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RCT1"
                    >Rowan</persName>.</p>
                <p>The President agreed, though apparently grudgingly. It was decided that the
                    approved directive, cleared by Defense, would be discussed in Honolulu with
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_NFEJ1">Nolting</persName> by Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> and Governor <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>. If the Ambassador concurs, the more
                    liberal policy would be confirmed by subsequent State telegram.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d73fn4">
                        <ref target="#d75">Document 75</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWH1">
                            <hi rend="strong">W.H.B.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
